<!-- ═══════════════ FAQ ═══════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="faq">
  <div class="container faq-container">
    <p class="overline">FAQ</p>
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">Everything travelers ask before visiting Little Boracay in Calatagan, Batangas.</p>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-item" open>
        <summary>What is Little Boracay in Calatagan, Batangas?</summary>
        <p>Little Boracay is a <strong>natural tidal sandbar</strong> off the western coast of Calatagan, Batangas, Philippines. Known for shallow turquoise waters, white sand, and iconic floating bamboo cottages. It is not a beach resort — it is a natural destination accessed by boat from the coastal barangays of Calatagan.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How far is Little Boracay from Manila?</summary>
        <p>Calatagan, Batangas is approximately <strong>3 to 4 hours from Metro Manila</strong> by car, depending on traffic. The route uses the South Luzon Expressway (SLEX) and STAR Tollway heading south toward Batangas.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Are floating cottages available at Little Boracay?</summary>
        <p>Yes. <strong>Floating bamboo cottages</strong> are one of the defining features of Little Boracay. They are available through local boat operators and provide shaded, over-water spaces for groups to relax, eat, and enjoy the sandbar environment.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Is Little Boracay the same as Boracay Island in Aklan?</summary>
        <p>No. Little Boracay is a <strong>separate destination</strong> in Calatagan, Batangas. It earned the nickname from similar white sand and turquoise water. Boracay Island is in Malay, Aklan and requires a flight and ferry from Manila.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the best time to visit Little Boracay?</summary>
        <p>Morning to early afternoon during low tide is best. The <strong>dry season from November to May</strong> offers the most reliable weather and calmest seas. Avoid typhoon season (June–October) when possible.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Is Little Boracay family-friendly?</summary>
        <p>Yes. The <strong>shallow, calm waters</strong> make it suitable for families including young children. Adult supervision is always recommended when swimming.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How far is it from CaSoBe or Stilts Beach Resort?</summary>
        <p>Both CaSoBe (Calatagan South Beach) and Stilts Beach Resort are located nearby along the Calatagan coastline. Many visitors combine multiple stops in a single day trip to the area.</p>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What should I bring to Little Boracay?</summary>
        <p>Essentials: <strong>cash (PHP)</strong>, high-SPF sunscreen, swimwear, waterproof sandals, dry bag for valuables, drinking water, packed food or snacks. Optional: snorkeling gear, waterproof camera, drone (check CAAP regulations).</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

